observations.recommendation:
We recommended and Management agreed to –

a) direct all personnel concerned to prepare APP and PPMP in accordance with Section 7 of IRR of R.A. No. 9184;

b) require the BAC Secretariat to retrieve and submit to the GPPB and Audit Team the final APP and PPMP for CY 2023;

c) instruct the BAC Secretariat to post all the awarded contract’s Notice of Award (NOA) and Notice to Proceed (NTP) on the municipality’s website; and

d) direct the BAC to prepare the Procurement Monitoring Report (PMR) within 14 calendar days after the end of each semester and submit it to GPBB, copy and furnish the Audit Team.

Enjoin the Municipal Accountant to adopt in full the Perpetual Inventory Method in his recording of inventories;

Require the concerned officer to maintain and submit the Summary of Supplies and Materials Issued (SSMI) together with the corresponding Requisition and Issue Slip (RIS) for the issued supplies/goods, and maintain stock cards for each item of Inventory to ensure proper accounting and promote better control in the receipt and issuance of supplies; and,

Ensure that the semestral count of Inventory items is promptly conducted, and the corresponding report is submitted on time to the Audit Team.

Strictly adhere to the required Accounting System/ General Accounting Plan for Local Government Units from the transactions to the preparation of Financial Statements as stated in Chapter 3 of LGU-NGAS Volume 1;

Enjoin the Municipal Accountant to immediately review the book balances and prepare adjusting entries for all the deficiencies/ inaccuracies discussed above;

For the Due to BIR account, enjoin the Municipal Accountant to trace the cause of the abnormal balance and if necessary, request for tax credit from the Bureau of Internal Revenue (BIR); and,

Enjoin the Municipal Account to timely reconcile bank records versus books balances and prepare necessary correcting entries.

Remove any signboard indicating the names and pictures associated with the top management of the implementing agency, and replace it with appropriate signboard/billboards indicating the project details within the project’s location in compliance with COA Circular 2013-004 to promote transparency and accountability and encourage citizen participation;

Inform the Audit Team Leader within ten days after the award of the infrastructure project and/or before the start of the program/activity of any postings of project signboards and/or public notice for validation by the audit team;

Ensure that a list of all on-going government PPAs and those that are to be implemented during the year are submitted to the audit team at the beginning of the year, and provided with complete information as indicated in Section 2.1 of COA Circular 2013-004; and,

Strictly comply with the regulations provided in COA Circular 2013-004.

Adhere strictly to the rules and regulations of GSIS, PhilHealth, and Pag-IBIG regarding proper withholding of premium payments and remittances thereof;

Verify immediately the cause of the difference between the year-end balance of Due to PhilHealth and the actual billing from the Agency and if warranted, request that the interests and penalties charged to the LGU be waived; and,

Enjoin employees to comply with the requirements of GSIS, PhilHealth, and Pag-IBIG to initiate immediate remittance of their premiums and come up with a management plan regarding the unremitted employee’s share whose contracts were not renewed.

Strategically plan the allocation of budget to identified Barangays under one project classification to ensure that the implementation of the same is fully realized;

Require the coordination between the concerned officers regarding the procedures for the receipt of procured materials in order to avoid the procedural lapse observed by the audit team; and,

Require the MA to follow the proper journal entries and the inventory process prescribed by MNGAS for LGUs pertaining to the receipt of and the issuance of construction materials inventory.

Conduct physical count of the local road networks and submit the Report on the Physical Count of the Road Network System;

Prepare the Report on Local Road Networks, maintain local road inventory, road map and property cards for all roads and its component;

Maintain subsidiary ledger cards for roads and road components of every road network and prepare lapsing schedule showing the computation of the depreciation of each component of the Road Network System account; and,

Provide a complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects.

institute measures to properly dispose all obsolete and unserviceable properties pursuant to the directives of Section 79 of PD 1445 and Sections 379-381 of RA 7160 and in accordance with the procedures cited in COA Circular No. 89-296;

instruct the Inventory Committee to update its IIRUP and indicate whether the listed PPEs are still in the custody or within the premises of the Municipality; 

If there are missing PPEs, assign personnel to locate/account the missing or non-existing items noted during the inventory taking or trace the documents of previous years to serve as reference to identify the accountable persons for the lost properties, investigate whether there is a need to demand settlement from the accountable persons and/or submit request for relief from accountability; and if warranted, facilitate the process of derecognition following the guidelines and provisions of applicable  COA Circulars; and,

For those unserviceable PPE that are still within their estimated useful life, conduct investigation to check whether there was negligence on the part of the custodians/ users of the PPEs. For the dump truck, check whether preventive maintenance services were availed from the authorized car dealer. Also, consult experts who can check whether the PPEs can still be repaired.

Require the Municipal Accountant to take-up or adjust in the books subject parcels of lots which were officially received by the LGU as government property at acquisition cost or fair market value in pursuant to Sections 26 and 27 of PPSAS 17 and Section 63 of PD 1445;

Instruct the Municipal Treasurer as the Property Custodian to maintain updated report of the LGU’s properties; and

Require the Municipal Assessor’s Office to facilitate the registration of the untitled land and/or transfer of title of the aforementioned parcels of lots in the name of the LGU with the Registry of Deeds.

We recommended that Management require the Municipal Accountant to:
Liquidate fund transfers once projects are fully implemented and/or refund the unutilized amount from completed projects and require the appropriate recording in the books of accounts;
Trace the transactions pertaining to the negative balance of ₱176,593.77 and prepare/maintain subsidiary ledgers indicating details of transactions such as the name of specific project, receipts, disbursements or any adjustments for the total balance of ₱2,635,436.42 as of December 31, 2024, otherwise, provide adequate disclosure in the notes to financial statements;
Ensure that a separate subsidiary record/ledger is maintained for each succeeding account/project; and,
Observe strict compliance with COA Circular No. 94-013 and monitor timely liquidation of expenditures/disbursements.

We recommended that Management direct the MT/GSO-designate to:
Ensure that all vehicles currently owned and will be purchased by the Municipality are properly registered with the LTO and regularly monitor its expiration and renewal of LTO registration;
See to it that all insurable assets and properties of the Municipality are adequately covered/insured;
Ensure that the inventory of OR, CR, and insurance policy certificates of the Municipality’s vehicles and other properties be under their custody and are properly kept, monitored, and renewed, regularly.

Recommendation:
Conduct the field survey and investigation satisfactorily and efficiently to prepare accurate design and production plans;
strategically implement its developmental projects within the target period of accomplishment to ensure that the 20 percent of the National Tax Allotment is optimally utilized in the prompt implementation of programs and projects to achieve the desired socio-economic development as prescribed under DBM-DOF-DILG JMC No. 1.

Recommendation:
We recommended and Management agreed to enjoin: 

the Municipal Accountant to designate a new Inventory Committee Head and if necessary, assign new committee members;

all concerned officers to coordinate and clarify as to who will conduct the complete physical count of all PPE and prepare the report; 

the creation of a committee composed of one personnel each from Treasurer’s Office and Accounting Office who shall reconcile their respective records of PPE on a full-time basis and at the same time maintain an updated and complete PPE Ledger Cards and Property Cards; 

For the Road Networks, direct the Municipal Accountant to record all road networks and its components, based on the Registry of Public Infrastructures, or in its absence, based on the complete Local Road Inventory Report provided with complete description and cost segregation of the road components and provide proper disclosure of the road networks in the Notes to Financial Statements;

direct the responsible officer to maintain an updated Local Road Inventory and Road Map and keep a complete Local Road Network Property Card of all roads within its area of jurisdiction; and 

if warranted, enjoin the Municipal Accountant to adjust in the books the discrepancies identified during the reconciliation.

